	volume = {15},
	abstract = {Though the process of meaning construction is widely recognized to be a crucialfactor in the mobilization, unfolding, and outcomes of social movements, the conditions a mechanisms that allow meaning construction and cultural transformation are oft misconceptualized and/or underanalyzed. Following a "tool kit" perspective on cul ture, dominant social movement theory locates meaning only as it is embodied in con crete social practices. Meaning construction from this perspective is a matter manipulating static symbols and meaning to achieve goals. I argue instead that mea ing is located in the structure of culture, and that the condition and mechanism meaning construction and transformation are, respectively, the metaphoric nature symbolic systems, and individual and collective interpretation of those systems in th face of concrete events. This theory is demonstrated by analyzing, through textual anla sis, meaning construction during the Irish Land War, 1879-1882, showing how dive social groups constructed new and emergent symbolic meanings and how transform collective understandings contributed to specific, yet unpredictable, political acti and movement outcomes. The theoretical model and empirical case demonstrates th social movement analysis must examine the metaphoric logic of symbolic systems a the interpretive process by which people construct meaning in order to fully explain t role of culture in social movements, the agency of movement participants, and t contingency of the course and outcomes of social movements},
